For 10k events/min, you're choosing between the operational simplicity of using your database as a queue and the predictable isolation of a dedicated message broker. Use the [Outbox Pattern](https://debezium.io/blog/2019/02/19/reliable-microservices-data-exchange-with-the-outbox-pattern/) if you need transactional guarantees (the event *must* ship if the DB record updates), but move to a managed queue like SQS if you want to avoid DB contention during bursts.

The primary trade-off is resource interference: [SKIP LOCKED](https://www.2ndquadrant.com/en/blog/what-is-select-for-update-skip-locked-in-postgresql-in-postgres-9-5/) allows you to build queues directly in Postgres, but high-frequency polling can bloat your transaction logs and spike IOPS, potentially starving user-facing queries [as noted in common Celery/DB-as-queue warnings](https://denibertovic.com/posts/celery-best-practices/). If you choose the DB path, keep your consumer logic extremely lean to minimize lock duration.

If you opt for SQS, you gain natural backpressure and infinite scalability, but you move from "exactly-once" transactional updates to "at-least-once" delivery. This necessitates an idempotency strategy: [never pass full state objects](https://github.com/sidekiq/sidekiq/wiki/Best-Practices) in your message payloads. Always pass the ID and force the worker to fetch the latest state from your DB, which handles potential retries or race conditions safely.

```sdanswer
{
  "type": "tradeoff",
  "title": "Postgres SKIP LOCKED vs. Managed Queue (SQS)",
  "options": [
    {
      "label": "Postgres SKIP LOCKED",
      "bullets": [
        "Transactional atomicity by default",
        "Zero infrastructure overhead",
        "Risk of DB IOPS contention",
        "Tied to DB scaling limits"
      ]
    },
    {
      "label": "Managed Queue (SQS)",
      "bullets": [
        "High isolation from DB",
        "Infinite throughput scalability",
        "Requires idempotency logic",
        "Adds network hop complexity"
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

Before you commit, ask yourself if your consumers can handle duplicates—if the answer is no, you'll need to invest in idempotency keys regardless of which transport you choose.

For a 10k-events/min burst workload, the choice depends on whether you prioritize transactional atomicity or infrastructure decoupling. At this scale, Postgres can handle the throughput, but the polling overhead often creates contention with your primary application queries.

If your events are generated as side effects of database changes, starting with a Postgres-backed outbox is the most reliable path. [Reliable Microservices Data Exchange With the Outbox Pattern](https://debezium.io/blog/2019/02/19/reliable-microservices-data-exchange-with-the-outbox-pattern/) explains how to use an outbox table to ensure your state changes and event emissions happen in a single transaction, providing "read your own writes" semantics that SQS can't offer natively. However, as noted in [Celery Best Practices](https://denibertovic.com/posts/celery-best-practices/), using your database as a broker introduces a scaling ceiling; aggressive polling for new jobs can eventually starve your user-facing connections during bursts.

If you move to SQS to decouple the load, you must shift your mental model to handle at-least-once delivery. A common mistake is passing full state objects in the message payload. [Sidekiq Best Practices](https://github.com/sidekiq/sidekiq/wiki/Best-Practices) recommends passing only simple identifiers (like an ID string) so the worker can fetch the fresh state from the database, which prevents race conditions where a worker processes stale data during a burst.

```sdanswer
{
  "type": "tradeoff",
  "title": "Postgres SKIP LOCKED vs. Managed SQS",
  "options": [
    {
      "label": "Postgres (Outbox)",
      "bullets": [
        "Atomic: Event + DB write succeed or fail together",
        "Consistency: Zero delay between write and visibility",
        "Risk: Polling load can impact primary DB performance"
      ]
    },
    {
      "label": "Managed SQS",
      "bullets": [
        "Scalable: Absorbs massive bursts without DB pressure",
        "Decoupled: Worker failures don't affect API uptime",
        "Risk: Requires idempotency for duplicate messages"
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

Before you commit to SQS, verify if your workers can handle messages out of order—standard SQS doesn't guarantee sequence, and FIFO queues have significantly lower throughput limits.

At 10k events/min, you're approaching the scale where Postgres `FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED` begins to sweat under lock contention and row bloat. SQS is the safer pick for raw throughput and built-in failure handling, but you'll likely want to use Postgres as a "transactional outbox" to keep your data consistent.

The primary risk with Postgres at this volume is the "spiral of death" described in [Transactionally Staged Job Drains in Postgres](https://brandur.org/job-drain). As workers frantically scan for available rows, MVCC overhead and long-running transactions can make it increasingly difficult to find locks, eventually causing your database to buckle. If you stay on Postgres, you'll need to be aggressive with indexing as outlined in [Use The Index, Luke!](https://use-the-index-luke.com/) to minimize the scan surface area.

Moving to SQS provides managed features like [Amazon SQS Dead-Letter Queues](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSSimpleQueueService/latest/SQSDeveloperGuide/sqs-dead-letter-queues.html), but you lose the ability to commit a job and a data change in a single transaction. To bridge this, implement the [Reliable Microservices Data Exchange With the Outbox Pattern](https://debezium.io/blog/2019/02/19/reliable-microservices-data-exchange-with-the-outbox-pattern/): write your events to a local Postgres "outbox" table within your business transaction, then use a background worker to drain those rows into SQS.

```sdanswer
{
  "type": "tradeoff",
  "title": "Postgres vs. Managed SQS",
  "options": [
    {
      "label": "Postgres (SKIP LOCKED)",
      "bullets": [
        "Strong transactional consistency",
        "Zero extra infra cost",
        "Subject to MVCC bloat",
        "Harder to scale bursts"
      ]
    },
    {
      "label": "Managed SQS",
      "bullets": [
        "Highly scalable throughput",
        "Built-in dead-letter queues",
        "Eventual consistency risk",
        "Network/API overhead"
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

If you stick with the Postgres-only path, monitor your `autovacuum` health closely—at 10k/min, the churn of "deleted" job rows can quickly outpace the default cleanup settings and tank your query performance.
